    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Hair, Skin &amp; Nails Gummies</h2>

    <details class="fq"><summary>Do hair, skin, and nails gummies actually work?</summary><p>Effectiveness depends on ingredients and deficiency status. Biotin supplementation significantly improves hair thickness and nail hardness in deficient individuals within 3-6 months. Collagen peptides improve skin elasticity and hydration in multiple clinical trials. For individuals with adequate nutrition, supplementation may provide minimal additional benefit.</p></details>

    <details class="fq"><summary>How long does it take to see results?</summary><p>Most studies show measurable hair and nail results at 3-6 months. Skin benefits from collagen may appear within 4-8 weeks. Hair grows about 0.5 inches per month, so visible changes require 2-3 months minimum. Consistency is critical.</p></details>

    <details class="fq"><summary>What is the most important ingredient?</summary><p>Biotin (2,500-5,000mcg) for hair and nails. Collagen peptides (2.5-10g daily) for skin. Vitamin C is essential as a cofactor for collagen synthesis. The best gummies combine all three.</p></details>

    <details class="fq"><summary>Can biotin cause acne?</summary><p>Some users report breakouts at 5,000-10,000mcg daily, possibly due to competition with vitamin B5 for absorption. Look for formulas that include pantothenic acid alongside biotin. Start at 2,500mcg before increasing.</p></details>

    <details class="fq"><summary>Are these gummies safe to take daily?</summary><p>Yes. Biotin is water-soluble with no established upper limit. Important: high-dose biotin can interfere with blood tests including troponin and thyroid panels. Inform your healthcare provider before blood work.</p></details>

    <details class="fq"><summary>Should men take hair, skin, and nails gummies?</summary><p>Absolutely. The biochemistry of hair, skin, and nail health is identical in both sexes. Men experiencing thinning hair, dry skin, or brittle nails may benefit equally. Male-pattern hair loss driven by DHT may require additional interventions.</p></details>

